DURBAN - The water situation in KwaZulu-Natal has improved slightly, with some dams filling up. But the province is not out of the woods just yet. Albert Falls Dam, which provides water to the province’s major cities is less than half full, and authorities are worried. While the recent rainfall brought some hope to the drought-stricken province, water users remain under pressure. READ: KZN water officials to monitor dam levels Authorities say climate change and a crippling drought have contributed to the current situation. With the winter season approaching, authorities are not expecting much rainfall and this will put further strain the water system. * Watch the full video report by Siphamandla Goge in the gallery above. eNCA